<div id="main_content">
	<h2>Experts Discuss Future of Iraq, Afghanistan</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Michael Napolitano
		
		<span class="date">March 31, 2010</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 345px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/2000/NE2107/en_US/speakersfull.jpg" height="226" width="345"  /> 
			
			<p>Jeff Smith and Scott Worden were two of the panelists at the forum organized by the UCF Global Perspectives Office.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=002400417c223ec20125ae9931fd05ec3">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:freeman@mail.ucf.edu">Mark Freeman, Global Perspectives</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-0935</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.ucfglobalperspectives.org">Global Perspectives Office</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>Experts on the conflicts in Iraq and Afghanistan shared their views during a public forum Tuesday, March 23, at the University of Central Florida.<br />
&ldquo;Iraq and Afghanistan in Flux,&rdquo; organized by the UCF Global Perspectives Office, drew an audience of nearly 150 people who listened intently as the speakers shared their insights on the two wars and their implications.</p>
<p>Isaac Kfir, the Schusterman Visiting Israeli Professor from Syracuse University and a senior researcher at the Institute for Counter-Terrorism in Herzliya, Israel, commented on the need to contain Afghanistan&rsquo;s crisis. He suggested that the United States needs to rethink the way it presents its Afghanistan policy, stating that &ldquo;the number of G.I.s and amount of money spent will be irrelevant until we understand our opponents.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Kfir also discussed the importance of the cultural history and religious demographics of the country. The tribal culture of the Pashtun, the founding ethnic group of Afghanistan, places great importance on the family unit and honor, he said.&nbsp; Kfir argued that this tribal culture, combined with religion and the economic situation in Afghanistan, must be understood if any progress is to be made.</p>
<p>Jeff Smith, the Kraemer Strategy Fellow at the American Foreign Policy Council in Washington, D.C., and editor of the organization&rsquo;s Eurasia Security Watch and South Asia Security Monitor, spoke on the tendency to downgrade Iraq&rsquo;s significance. He stated that Iraq is of &ldquo;great strategic importance&rdquo; and &ldquo;will require our utmost attention and resources.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>His focus was mainly on the political situation, specifically the problems and prospects of a democratic system in Iraq. Smith warned that Shi&rsquo;a Muslims &ndash; the majority in Iraq but the minority within the region &ndash; are becoming marginalized, but the United States wants to keep them active in the political arena. He also noted that the political system in Iraq is based on alliances, and it is unclear what will happen as the parties vie for power.</p>
<p>Scott Worden, a senior adviser in the Rule of Law Center of Innovation for the United States Institute of Peace in Washington, D.C., and a former advisor to the U.N. Assistance Mission in Afghanistan on human rights and elections issues, focused on elections. Worden, who was also an advisor to the Afghanistan Joint Election Management Body on the conduct of the 2005 parliamentary elections, looked at Afghanistan through a &ldquo;political lens,&rdquo; stating that we are &ldquo;back at the beginning.&rdquo;&nbsp;</p>
<p>He argued that the years between 2006 and 2009 were a lost opportunity in the country, with the 2009 elections demonstrating the extent of the corruption. Those elections &ldquo;failed the stress test of the strength of Afghanistan&rsquo;s democracy,&rdquo; Worden said, and the corrupt democratic process &ldquo;hurt the image of the government.&rdquo; He questioned if the United States has the leverage to push for the reform that has yet to be seen in the country.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Worden stated that completely shutting out the Taliban from Afghan politics upon formation of the new government was a mistake and that the decision to talk with the Taliban will prove productive. He stressed the need to marginalize corrupt actors and that a credible parliament is important to establishing a government in Afghanistan.&nbsp; He also emphasized the importance of local governments in rural areas and underscored that local elections have yet to be held.</p>
<p>All three speakers stressed the importance of international assistance in forming democratic governments in both Iraq and Afghanistan. Worden acknowledged that the imposition of a progressive Western system could be shocking and counter-productive, but went on to suggest that there must be&nbsp; some &ldquo;jump-starting&rdquo; of the system, given the absence of a cultural background in democracy among Arabs.</p>
<p>Kfir said the Afghan people are very open to the ideas of democracy and that the country has actually had many attempts at democracy. Smith argued that democracy is actually the absence of imposition, as it involves the people creating their own laws and having the right to vote. He also suggested that it is the United States&rsquo; responsibility to aid in this venture, as the U.S. government has backed dictators in the region for decades.</p>
<p>In addition to the Global Perspectives Office, sponsors included the UCF Middle East Studies Program, Kurdish Political Studies Initiative, Diplomacy Program, Terrorism Studies Program, Political Science Department and International Services Center, UCF LIFE and the Global Connections Foundation.</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands For Opportunity:</strong> The University of Central Florida is a metropolitan research university that ranks as the 3rd largest in the nation with more than 53,500 students. UCF's first classes were offered in 1968. The university offers impressive academic and research environments that power the region's economic development. UCF's culture of opportunity is driven by our diversity, Orlando environment, history of entrepreneurship and our youth, relevance and energy. For more information, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
